      "source": [
        "## Gender and Churn Distribution Analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "###  1. Gender Distribution\n",
        "- The **Gender** chart shows that the customer base is **almost evenly split**:\n",
        "  - **Male:** 49.5%\n",
        "  - **Female:** 50.5%\n",
        "-  This indicates there is **no significant gender imbalance** in the dataset.  \n",
        "- Since both genders are almost equally represented, **gender alone may not have a strong impact** on customer churn — further analysis will be required to confirm this.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "###  2. Churn Distribution\n",
        "- The **Churn** chart shows:\n",
        "  - **No (did not churn):** 73.4%\n",
        "  - **Yes (churned):** 26.6%\n",
        "- This means that about **one in every four customers left the company**.\n",
        "-  The dataset is **slightly imbalanced**, as the number of customers who stayed (73.4%) is much higher than those who left (26.6%).\n",
        "- When building predictive models, this imbalance should be addressed using techniques such as:\n",
        "  - **Resampling** (e.g., SMOTE or Random Oversampling)\n",
        "  - **Adjusting class weights** in the model.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "###  Insights\n",
        "- Gender distribution is balanced → good for unbiased modeling.\n",
        "- Churn distribution is imbalanced → needs consideration during model training.\n",
        "- The churn rate (26.6%) is quite significant for a telecom business, meaning that **reducing churn could substantially improve customer retention and revenue**.\n"
      ]
    },
